As an introverted creative to be self-employed and to place great value on one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (bad) tech giants and being extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark from that service, be available 24/7, answer queries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
Werben Sie hier, folgen Sie dem Algorithmus, zeigen Sie Ihre Persönlichkeit.
For me, it's a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to sell it to everyone. I'm on the lookout for new ways to run my business and at the same time I'm fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do something in a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I've cancelled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I've cancelled my Google Analytics account, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will be relocating my business there in the coming weeks.
I've transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for normal email validation.
I've been searching for alternative ways to exist as a self-employed creative, without being dependent on the tech giants.
I've been searching for alternative ways to run my business, without relying on the services of tech giants like Facebook.
As a photographer, it really delights me to read your thread! I know it's not easy mentally to step back from commercial social media, but you free your head up for so many other things.
